w to draw a single dotted or dashed line in Photoshop CC 2014','','inherit','closed','open','','533-revision-v1','','','2014-09-30 17:44:58','2014-09-30 16:44:58','',533,'http://ptrck.nl/533-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(548,1,'2014-09-30 17:46:06','2014-09-30 16:46:06','OK, so we can do dotted and dashed strokes on a path now in Photoshop CC and CC 2014. Awesome. This works on shapes. But how to create a single (1px or 1pt) line that could be used for example as a divider in your interface design?\r\n<h2>1. Draw with Line Tool? No.</h2>\r\nNope. Photoshop actually creates a 1px rectangular shape with strokes on both sides. With a 1px or 1pt stroke this doubles your stroke and messes up appearance. (Does anybody ever use the Line Tool?)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-538 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-1-1-Line-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Line Tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"57\" />\r\n<h2>2. Draw with the Pen Tool? No.</h2>\r\nShould work, but doesn’t. The path line is there. But whatever stroke option you pick isn’t.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-539 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-2-2-Pen-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Pen Tool\" width=\"1428\" height=\"123\" />\r\n<h2>3. Delete Anchor Point Tool from an existing shape? No.</h2>\r\nWould be a nice hack. Doesn’t work. By removing points the shape is still in tact. Not sure how that works when 2 points are left, but it simply doesn’t fill, and it doesn’t stroke. Too bad.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-540 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-3-delete-tool.gif\" alt=\"example 3 delete tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"209\" />\r\n<h2>4. Select anchor point and press BACKSPACE/DELETE. Yes!</h2>\r\nYes! Almost similar to the previous. The shape doesn’t connect as a whole anymore. The final path with two open ended anchor points get a nice stroke between them. \r\n\r\nThis is the way to go. Select with the Direct Selection Tool (White Arrow) and press backspace or delete.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-541 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-4-delete-backspace.gif\" alt=\"example 4 delete backspace\" wwidth=\"670\" height=\"209\" />','How to draw a single dotted or dashed line in Photoshop CC 2014','','inherit','closed','open','','533-revision-v1','','','2014-09-30 17:46:06','2014-09-30 16:46:06','',533,'http://ptrck.nl/533-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(549,1,'2014-09-30 17:46:29','2014-09-30 16:46:29','OK, so we can do dotted and dashed strokes on a path now in Photoshop CC and CC 2014. Awesome. This works on shapes. But how to create a single (1px or 1pt) line that could be used for example as a divider in your interface design?\r\n<h2>1. Draw with Line Tool? No.</h2>\r\nNope. Photoshop actually creates a 1px rectangular shape with strokes on both sides. With a 1px or 1pt stroke this doubles your stroke and messes up appearance. (Does anybody ever use the Line Tool?)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-538 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-1-1-Line-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Line Tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"57\" />\r\n<h2>2. Draw with the Pen Tool? No.</h2>\r\nShould work, but doesn’t. The path line is there. But whatever stroke option you pick isn’t.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-539 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-2-2-Pen-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Pen Tool\" width=\"1428\" height=\"123\" />\r\n<h2>3. Delete Anchor Point Tool from an existing shape? No.</h2>\r\nWould be a nice hack. Doesn’t work. By removing points the shape is still in tact. Not sure how that works when 2 points are left, but it simply doesn’t fill, and it doesn’t stroke. Too bad.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-540 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-3-delete-tool.gif\" alt=\"example 3 delete tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"209\" />\r\n<h2>4. Select anchor point and press BACKSPACE/DELETE. Yes!</h2>\r\nYes! Almost similar to the previous. The shape doesn’t connect as a whole anymore. The final path with two open ended anchor points get a nice stroke between them. \r\n\r\nThis is the way to go. Select an anchor point with the Direct Selection Tool (White Arrow) and press backspace or delete.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-541 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-4-delete-backspace.gif\" alt=\"example 4 delete backspace\" wwidth=\"670\" height=\"209\" />','How to draw a single dotted or dashed line in Photoshop CC 2014','','inherit','closed','open','','533-revision-v1','','','2014-09-30 17:46:29','2014-09-30 16:46:29','',533,'http://ptrck.nl/533-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(551,1,'2014-09-30 17:49:53','2014-09-30 16:49:53','','stroke options@2x','','inherit','closed','open','','stroke-options2x','','','2014-09-30 17:49:53','2014-09-30 16:49:53','',533,'http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/stroke-options@2x.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(552,1,'2014-09-30 17:51:43','2014-09-30 16:51:43','<p>OK, so we can do dotted and dashed strokes on a path now in Photoshop CC and CC 2014. Awesome. This works on shapes. But how to create a single (1px or 1pt) line that could be used for example as a divider in your interface design?<br /><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-551\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/stroke-options@2x.png\" alt=\"stroke options@2x\" width=\"249\" height=\"274\" /></p>\r\n<h2>1. Draw with Line Tool? No.</h2>\r\nNope. Photoshop actually creates a 1px rectangular shape with strokes on both sides. With a 1px or 1pt stroke this doubles your stroke and messes up appearance. (Does anybody ever use the Line Tool?)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-538 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-1-1-Line-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Line Tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"57\" />\r\n<h2>2. Draw with the Pen Tool? No.</h2>\r\nShould work, but doesn’t. The path line is there. But whatever stroke option you pick isn’t. Frustrating...\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-539 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-2-2-Pen-Tool.gif\" alt=\"Drawing a line using the Pen Tool\" width=\"1428\" height=\"123\" />\r\n<h2>3. Delete Anchor Point Tool from an existing shape? No.</h2>\r\nWould be a nice hack. Doesn’t work. By removing points the shape is still in tact. Not sure how that works when 2 points are left, but it simply doesn’t fill, and it doesn’t stroke. Too bad.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-540 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-3-delete-tool.gif\" alt=\"example 3 delete tool\" width=\"670\" height=\"209\" />\r\n<h2>4. Select anchor point and press BACKSPACE/DELETE. Yes!</h2>\r\nYes! Almost similar to the previous. The shape doesn’t connect as a whole anymore. The final path with two open ended anchor points get a nice stroke between them.\r\n\r\nThis is the way to go. Select an anchor point with the Direct Selection Tool (White Arrow) and press backspace or delete.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-541 size-full\" src=\"http://ptrck.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/example-4-delete-backspace.gif\" alt=\"example 4 delete backspace\" height=\"209\" />','How to draw a single dotted or dashed line in Photoshop CC 2014','','inherit','closed','open','','533-revision-v1','','','2014-09-30 17:51:43','2014-09-30 16:51:43','',533,'http://ptrck.nl/533-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(554,1,'2015-08-21 14:02:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','What happened?\r\nI switched to selling mode...\r\nShould have kept in feedback mode.\r\n\r\nSuch a simple concept. I’ll explain:\r\n<h3>I scheduled a demo with an offer.</h3>\r\nI asked for feedback every single slide.\r\nI made sure I understood him correctly.\r\nI made adjustments where needed.\r\nI pre-sold effortlessly.\r\n<h3>This successful sale felt like magic.</h3>\r\n<h3>Until I (unconsciously) switched to selling mode.</h3>\r\nDuh.\r\nI thought: ‘Yay! Now let’s speed this up and get as many more people on board as possible.\'\r\nI wasn’t focusing on feedback anymore.\r\nI was focusing on selling.\r\n\r\nDidn’t notice it. Until:\r\n<h3>Boom! Objection</h3>\r\nThe pre-sale didn’t complete.\r\nInstead, I got an objection on the sale.\r\n(How do we measure results?)\r\nI was in selling mode.\r\nThis felt like a failed sale, because I didn’t have a way to solve it.\r\n<h3>This instantly disqualified all the people I was looking to sell to as well.</h3>\r\n<h3>I tried to ‘fix’ the objection and ‘fix’ the sale.</h3>\r\nMy mindset was still in selling mode.\r\nSo getting back to my prospect felt like trying to save the sale.\r\nOops, I was still selling!\r\n<h3>I gathered solutions to sell.</h3>\r\nYes I gathered possible solutions handling the objection.\r\nYes I gathered ideas on improving my offer.\r\nIn fact, because I was still in my ‘sale-mindset’ I gathered information to fix the sale.\r\n<h3>So I got stuck.</h3>\r\nI felt my product was flawed.\r\nI felt I would get just one take to fix it.\r\nI felt it would have to be perfect now.\r\nI started to feel miserable.\r\n<h3>Going back to the pre-selling report, I realised something.</h3>\r\nThe most important thing you need to do in your demos is:\r\nGather feedback so you can iterate on your product until it’s a must-have product for them.\r\n<h3>So I switched to feedback mode.</h3>\r\nThis finally allowed me to see things from a different perspective again.\r\n<h3>A. I saw the presale objection differently.</h3>\r\nI didn’t try to ‘save\' the sale anymore.\r\nI went back to looking for feedback on a possible solution.\r\nI went back to looking for feedback on a possible improved offer.\r\n<h3>B. I saw meetings with potential new customers differently.</h3>\r\nI didn’t look to schedule meetings and demos with my now ‘ought to be perfect’ product and offer.\r\nI started looking to schedule demos to show a possible solution:\r\n- Did I understand the problem correctly?\r\n- Would this try to solve it for you?\r\n- Does it make sense to calculate ROI like this?\r\n- Would you be interested in becoming a (champion) user?\r\n- Would it help your business to pay this monthly price to receive 10x the value for this product?\r\n<h3>I went back to looking for feedback until the sale was a natural conclusion to the steps taken so far.</h3>\r\nMade so much sense.\r\nIt freed up my mind, and I was ready for action again.\r\n\r\nFeedback mode is still selling. But in a much more natural and organic way.','How I got stuck by a pre-sale objection and got unstuck again','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2015-08-21 14:02:14','2015-08-21 13:02:14','',0,'http://ptrck.nl/?p=554',0,'post','',0),(555,1,'2015-08-21 13:51:57','2015-08-21 12:51:57','What happened?\r\nI switched to selling mode...\r\nShould have kept in feedback mode.\r\n\r\nSuch a simple concept. I’ll explain:\r\n\r\n<strong>I scheduled a demo with an offer.</strong>\r\nI asked for feedback every single slide.\r\nI made sure I understood him correctly.\r\nI made adjustments where needed.\r\nI pre-sold effortlessly.\r\n\r\n<strong>This successful sale felt like magic.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Until I (unconsciously) switched to selling mode.</strong>\r\nDuh.\r\nI thought: ‘Yay! Now let’s speed this up and get as many more people on board as possible.\'\r\nI wasn’t focusing on feedback anymore.\r\nI was focusing on selling.\r\n\r\nDidn’t notice it. Until:\r\n\r\n<strong>Boom! Objection</strong>\r\nThe pre-sale didn’t complete.\r\nInstead, I got an objection on the sale.\r\n(How do we measure results?)\r\nI was in selling mode.\r\nThis felt like a failed sale, because I didn’t have a way to solve it.\r\n\r\n<strong>This instantly disqualified all the people I was looking to sell to as well.</s